April 29 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  SIEMENS AND GE IN RIVAL EFFORTS TO WOO PARIS (http://link.reuters.com/mej88v)  THREE FORMER US BARCLAYS TRADERS FACE CHARGES IN UK LIBOR PROBE (http://link.reuters.com/qej88v)  U.S. warns web users to log off IE (http://link.reuters.com/pej88v)  DISSENT AT SEC OVER BANK WAIVERS (http://link.reuters.com/nej88v)  INVESCO PERPETUAL FINED 18.6 MLN STG BY FCA FOR RULE BREACHES (http://link.reuters.com/rej88v)  Overview  General Electric <GE.N> Siemens <SIEGn.DE> on Monday began wooing France's socialist government in the hopes of winning it over to their rival bids for engineering group Alstom <ALSO.PA>, each arguing that its offer best served the national interest.  Three U.S.-based former Barclays <BARC.L> traders will be charged by Britain's Serious Fraud Office as part of its probe into the alleged manipulation of the Libor interbank rate.  The U.S. department of homeland security has told individuals and companies to avoid using Internet Explorer, after a flaw allowing cyber criminals to impersonate known websites and steal user data was found in the popular web browser.  U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission commissioner Kara Stein has accused the agency of having "strayed from its mission" by allowing two banks that pleaded guilty to interest-rate rigging to access capital markets without regulatory scrutiny.